Alibaba.com, China Southern, Huadian: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-26T01:01:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-26/alibaba-com-china-southern-huadian-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.1 percent to 22,747.28. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 0.1 percent to 12,689.66.  Airlines: China’s airlines can increase fuel surcharges on
domestic routes longer than 800 kilometers to 140 yuan ($21.56)
from 90 yuan from today, Shanghai Daily said, citing the
National Development and Reform Commission.  China Southern Airlines Co. (1055 HK),  Asia ’s largest
carrier by passenger numbers, fell 2.9 percent to HK$4.04. China
Eastern Airlines Corp. (670 HK), the nation’s No. 2 carrier by
passenger numbers, sank 2.9 percent to HK$3.38.  Alibaba.com Ltd. (1688)  (1688 HK): Yahoo! Inc. (YHOO US) Chief
Executive Officer  Carol Bartz  said she’s making “significant”
progress in talks to ensure Alibaba.com’s parent Alibaba Group
Holding Ltd., a company Yahoo partly owns, is compensated for
the spinoff of its payment business.  Yahoo, the biggest shareholder of China’s Alibaba Group,
has been negotiating with the company over the loss of Alipay, a
payment business that was spun off last summer. Alibaba.com,
owner of China’s biggest online-commerce site for businesses,
dropped 1.5 percent to HK$12.88.  Huadian Power International Corp. (1071 HK): China’s
fourth-biggest electricity producer said it received approval
for investments in two wind power projects. The stock retreated
1.2 percent to HK$1.69.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): The world’s biggest
developer sold 33 villas in the second phase of its Lake Dragon
project in Guangzhou at between 8 million yuan and 16 million
yuan, the Standard said, without citing anyone. The sales
yesterday are the first from this phase of the development,
which has 79 villas and 124 apartments in nine towers, the
report said. The stock was unchanged at HK$118.20.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story: Nick Gentle at
   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 